04626nam a22006375i 9780674031180DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222005mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740311807 a10.4159/97806740311802doi  a(DE-B1597)584836  a(OCoLC)1322125520  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHF5415.33.E85 ǂb D4 2005eb 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a306.309409041 aDe Grazia, Victoria, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIrresistible Empire :bAmerica’s Advance through Twentieth-Century Europe /cVictoria De Grazia. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (608 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Fast Way to Peace -- t1. The Service Ethic -- t2. A Decent Standard of Living -- t3. The Chain Store -- t4. Big-Brand Goods -- t5. Corporate Advertising -- t6. The Star System -- t7. The Consumer-Citizen -- t8. Supermarketing -- t9. A Model Mrs. Consumer -- tConclusion: How the Slow Movement Put Perspective on the Fast Life -- tNotes -- tBibliographic Essay -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"The most significant conquest of the twentieth century may well have been the triumph of American consumer society over Europe’s bourgeois civilization. It is this little-understood but world-shaking campaign that unfolds in Irresistible Empire, Victoria de Grazia’s brilliant account of how the American standard of living defeated the European way of life and achieved the global cultural hegemony that is both its great strength and its key weakness today. De Grazia describes how, as America’s market empire advanced with confidence through Europe, spreading consumer-oriented capitalism, all alternative strategies fell before it—first the bourgeois lifestyle, then the Third Reich’s command consumption, and finally the grand experiment of Soviet-style socialist planning. Tracing the peculiar alliance that arrayed New World salesmanship, statecraft, and standardized goods against the Old World’s values of status, craft, and good taste, Victoria de Grazia follows the United States’ market-driven imperialism through a vivid series of cross-Atlantic incursions by the great inventions of American consumer society. We see Rotarians from Duluth in the company of the high bourgeoisie of Dresden; working-class spectators in ramshackle French theaters conversing with Garbo and Bogart; Stetson-hatted entrepreneurs from Kansas in the midst of fussy Milanese shoppers; and, against the backdrop of Rome’s Spanish Steps and Paris’s Opera Comique, Fast Food in a showdown with advocates for Slow Food. Demonstrating the intricacies of America’s advance, de Grazia offers an intimate and historical dimension to debates over America’s exercise of soft power and the process known as Americanization. She raises provocative questions about the quality of the good life, democracy, and peace that issue from the vaunted victory of mass consumer culture."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674031180?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674031180423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674031180/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK